#: mop/data/projects/idcew.py:43
msgid ""
"Helen – a Catholic Noblewoman, Serbian Queen and Interreligious Donor "
"connecting East and West in the 13th/14th Centuries (IDCEW)"
msgstr ""
"Helen – a Catholic Noblewoman, Serbian Queen and Interreligious Donor "
"connecting East and West in the 13th/14th Centuries (IDCEW)"

#: mop/data/projects/idcew.py:57
msgid "idcew_description_1"
msgstr ""
"The project aims to address the life and deeds of the medieval Serbian "
"Queen Helen, who lived in the 13th/14th centuries and was married to the "
"Serbian King Uroš I. It will be conducted in cooperation with the "
"Austrian Archaeological Institute (ÖAI) of the Austrian Academy of "
"Sciences with regard to the surveys and drone documentation in the area "
"of research. Helen’s life has to be understood as a person, who was "
"building bridges between the Orthodox East and the Latin West due to her "
"French descent and her strong relationship with the noble family of "
"Anjou. Many questions regarding Helen’s life, realm and endowments need "
"further in-depth research."

#: mop/data/projects/idcew.py:58
msgid "idcew_description_2"
msgstr ""
"These questions include:\n"
"<ul>\n"
"<li>A re-evaluation of Helen’s documents (i.e. charters and letters) in "
"order to define her realm in Zeta, Trebinje, Plav and the upper flow of "
"the river Ibar more precisely (also with the means of Cartography, "
"Toponymy and GIS)</li>\n"
"<li>In this context a new edition of the charters to the Monastery Sveti "
"Nikola na Vranjini, which have not been adequately edited until now and "
"which will contribute to our research questions</li>\n"
"<li>A reconstruction of the “Sacred Landscape” (contact zone) of Helen’s "
"realm by analysing the architecture of respective monuments (churches and"
" monasteries) of the 13th and 14th centuries, especially Sopoćani and "
"Gradac, in the Raški and Moravički okruzi (Serbia) with regard to Eastern"
" (Orthodox) and Western (Latin, Catholic) influences</li>\n"
"<li>The donations of icons and other small objects of art by Helen to "
"churches and monasteries in her realm as well as in Italy (cf. the icon "
"of the Saints Peter and Paul in the Vatican), their analysis with regard "
"to Eastern (Orthodox) and Western (Latin, Catholic) influences and "
"Helen’s afterlife in Serbian art of the 18th and 19th centuries</li>\n"
"</ul>"

